{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476772"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:51:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:51:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13946"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13946"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0.66,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6576"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35233"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"475"},{"type":"tags","id":"1021"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"},{"type":"tags","id":"5372"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13276"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with severe malnutrition due to anorexia nervosa. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears cachectic with a pulse rate of 50/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her body mass index is 14 kg/m2. After initial stabilisation and admission to the paediatric ward, a nasogastric feeding tube is inserted, and feeding is commenced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following biochemical abnormalities is most likely to develop in the next few days?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypermagnesaemia","Hyperkalaemia","Hypophosphataemia","Hypercalcaemia","Hyponatraemia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario described here is characteristic of the refeeding syndrome. Refeeding syndrome occurs when nutrition is reintroduced after a period of prolonged malnutrition or starvation, as seen in this case of a severely malnourished patient with anorexia nervosa. The most characteristic biochemical abnormality of refeeding syndrome is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypophosphataemia\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring prolonged starvation, the body adapts to using ketones and fatty acids as primary energy sources. When carbohydrates are reintroduced, there is a sudden shift back to glucose metabolism, leading to increased insulin secretion. This causes a rapid intracellular shift of phosphate, along with potassium and magnesium, resulting in severe hypophosphataemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with refeeding syndrome. In fact, sodium levels often remain relatively stable or may even increase slightly due to increased carbohydrate intake and subsequent fluid retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of refeeding syndrome. On the contrary, hypokalaemia is more commonly observed due to the intracellular shift of potassium in response to insulin release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypermagnesaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of refeeding syndrome. Similar to phosphate and potassium, magnesium levels typically decrease due to intracellular shift and increased demand for ATP production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with refeeding syndrome. Calcium levels may fluctuate but are generally not significantly affected in the early stages of refeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to appreciate that while hypophosphataemia is the most characteristic abnormality associated with the refeeding syndrome, other electrolyte imbalances, including hypokalaemia and hypomagnesaemia can also occur. Careful monitoring and gradual reintroduction of nutrition are essential in preventing and managing refeeding syndrome in severely malnourished patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypophosphataemia is the most characteristic biochemical abnormality in refeeding syndrome.","Refeeding syndrome can occur when nutrition is reintroduced after a period of prolonged malnutrition or starvation.","Careful monitoring and gradual reintroduction of nutrition are essential in preventing refeeding syndrome."],"references":["Roberts, I. Nelson\u2019s textbook of pediatrics (20th edn.), by R. Kliegman, B. Stanton, J. St. Geme, N. Schor (eds). Pediatr Radiol 47, 1364\u20131365 (2017). https://doi.org/10.1007/s00247-017-3907-9"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35233"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13946"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35233"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-05T08:44:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-05T08:44:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6576"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","i